AGI - The European Commission has today published its action plan for steel and metals, which intervenes to maintain and expand European industrial capacities, strengthen the competitiveness of the sector and ensure its future. "The European steel industry is fundamental for the EU economy, providing raw materials to key sectors such as automotive, clean technologies and defense. A solid steel and metal industry in Europe is crucial to ensure EU security in the current geopolitical context and to implement the 'Readiness 2030' plan, also presented today," says the EU Commission.
"At the same time, the sector is at a critical turning point, facing high energy costs, unfair global competition and the need for investment to reduce greenhouse gas emissions. The plan is introduced at a time when market distorsive measures, such as non-market support to global overcapacity and unjustified duties on steel and EU aluminium, can have a negative impact on our economy," reads again in the note accompanying the plan. "The steel industry has always been a central engine of European prosperity. The new generation steel, clean, must continue to be produced in Europe. This means that we have to support our steel producers, who face strong contrary winds on the global market. To ensure its competitiveness, we must reduce energy costs and help them to market innovative technologies with low carbon emissions. With today's action plan we offer concrete solutions for a flourishing European steel industry," said the Commission President, Ursula von der Leyen.
The action plan provides for measures to ensure safe and affordable energy supply for the sector, through the use of energy purchasing agreements, and encourages Member States to exploit fiscal flexibility on energy and reduced network rates to reduce electricity price volatility. The plan also supports faster access to the network for energy-intensive industries and promotes the growing use of renewable hydrogen and low carbon emissions in the industry. In order to prevent relocation of carbon emissions, the Commission plans to publish a communication on how to address the issue of carbon leakage for CBAM products exported from the EU to third countries, and to conduct a revision of CBAM, with a first legislative proposal by the end of 2025 to extend its scope to certain steel and aluminium products downstream and to include further anti-elusion measures. &nbsp;
In order to expand and protect European industrial capacities and counter the excess of global capacity, the plan plans to strengthen current safeguard measures for steel: Before the end of the year, the Commission will propose a new long-term measure to maintain a highly effective protection of the steel industry after the expiry of the current safeguard in mid-2026. In order to prevent exporters from advocating commercial defence measures, the Commission will also assess the introduction of the "melted and poured" rule to determine the origin of metal products.&nbsp;
On recycling and circularity, the Commission plans to set targets for the use of recycled steel and aluminium in key sectors and to assess whether more products, such as construction materials and electronics, should be subject to recycling or recycled content requirements. In addition, the Commission will examine commercial measures for scrap metal to ensure sufficient availability.
Regarding the decarbonization of the sector, the future Industrial Decarbonisation Accelerator Act will introduce resilience and sustainability criteria for European products in public procurement, in order to stimulate demand for low-emission metals produced in the EU, creating leading markets. The Commission will allocate 150 million euros through the research fund for coal and steel in 2026-27, with another 600 million euros through Horizon Europe dedicated to the Clean Industrial Deal. In the expansion phase, the Commission aims at EUR 100 billion through the Bank for Industrial Decarbonization, drawing on the Innovation Fund and other sources, with a pilot auction of EUR 1 billion in 2025 focused on decarbonization and electrification of key industrial processes.<br> &nbsp;

