AGI - The climate in Serbia continues to be glowing. After the hundreds of thousands of protesters on Saturday flooded the streets of Belgrade, giving rise to the biggest protest in the history of the country, this morning Parliament welcomed the resignation of Prime Minister Milos Vucevic > and of the entire government. Presented on 28 January after the serious incidents and occurred in Novi Sad in the margin of another manifestation of the student movement, resignations make the country increasingly unstable, both from a social and political point of view.
From November - every weekend - the capital becomes a destination of thousands of people, especially young people, to protest against the system of corruption that according to the protesters continues to spread in the country and to be also the cause of the incident occurred in Novi Sad> that cost fifteen people life.
<div </div
In the last few hours the tension continued to grow, especially after the accusations addressed to the Serbian police to have targeted the protesters on Saturday with an auditory device, a "sound dog" to control and disperse the crowd. The accusation was born after the spread of some footage showing thousands of people who suddenly moved away for apparently unknown reasons, pushing to assert that they had been targeted by a sonic weapon or, in fact, a "sound cannone").
A petition launched by activists - who reportedly collected more than half a million signatures - asked for a rapid and official investigation by the United Nations, while the police, the Ministry of Defense, the security agency and the government firmly denied the use of such a device. With the approval of Parliament's resignation, the government, set up on 2 May, will remain in office only for the care of current affairs.
<div </div
&nbsp;
Immediately after today's sitting, Parliament's President Ana Brnabic recalled the rule of law for which Parliament took a 30-day period from the taking of the government's resignation. If this is not to happen, new elections will be convened which, in this case, should possibly be held at the beginning of June. The idea of the political authorities of Belgrade, President Vucic>, Prime Minister and Head of Parliament - is to try to build a new government within a month, avoiding a transitional executive that ferries the country to vote, as required by opposition. &nbsp;
